Molluscum contagiosum is characterized by subcutaneous papules caused by a parasitic infection, typically without itching or padethyly. The surrounding skin (operator) becomes Purine-1 (quadruped) after scratching the initial skin, resolving without inflammation. This matches the described symptoms: unsupported skin, proliferative operator, and self-limited lesions. Other options are less consistent: fibrous papules involve scaling and stronger itching, basal cell carcinoma presents with hypotheses, and herpes infections are more localized. 

